            </rs>.</p>
               <p>SAMUEL WILLIAM THOMAS. I was by the Horse Guards on the 16th of March - Boston came and said I had lost my handkerchief - I felt, and missed it; the prisoner was taken into custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-246-person1370">
                  JOHN 
                  BOSTON
               <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1370" type="surname" value="BOSTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1370" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1370" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in <placeName id="t18280410-246-crimeloc1310">St. James' Park</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-246-crimeloc1310" type="placeName" value="St. James' Park"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-246-crimeloc1310" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-246-off1308 t18280410-246-crimeloc1310"></join>, and saw the prisoner, with Butcher and Clifford; they went up to the prosecutor, and I saw them turn from him; I and my brother officer seized them, and I saw this handkerchief fall down between them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-246-person1371">
                  THOMAS 
                  ROBERTS
               <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1371" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1371" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1371" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was there that morning at the time of relieving guard; I saw the prisoner take the handkerchief out of the prosecutor's pocket - the others were close to him; they were all seized, but the bill was thrown out against the others.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182804100111"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-246-person1372">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WHITTINGHAM
               <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1372" type="surname" value="WHITTINGHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1372" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1372" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in Parliament-street, and saw the prisoner with the others, but I did not see them taken.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I never picked the gentleman's pocket; Boston and Roberts cannot be believed; one of them was here for perjuring himself, and the other for lead stealing.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-246-person1373">
                  JOHN 
                  BOSTON
               <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1373" type="surname" value="BOSTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1373" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-246-person1373" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was tried here about five years ago for a lamp which I pawned while I was in service; I was in prison three months, and since then I have got a little place as porter at an upholsterer's.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280410-246-verdict1311" type="verdictDescription">
